-09-15 09:00:00','2011-09-15 11:00:00','2011-06-30 15:34:01','2011-07-11 14:47:53',1,NULL),(114,'Best Scenes in Town Challenge',6,'<b>ʻBest Scene in Townʼ</b> is a mobile design challenge that explores how we can interact with the city through our mobile phones. In ʻBest Scene in Townʼ student teams enter a series of hands-on creative sessions to design, develop and ultimately pilot their mobile concepts for a\r\nlive audience with the 7scenes platform.\r\nʻBest Scene in Townʼ challenges are big and small, but always push the boundaries of mobile\r\ninteraction. The challenge has been organized with several partners for different city themes\r\nover the last year and is focused at the new young professional – the university student.\r\nWith the PICNIC festival and Amsterdam Innovation Motor the challenge has found great\r\npartners in realizing the ambition of connecting international universities with each other.\r\n\r\n<b>ʻBest Scene in Townʼ @ PICNIC ʻ11</b>\r\nFollowing last year\'s success, the challenge has grown even larger with students participating from Parsons - The New School for Design (US), MIT (US), Hong Kong Design Institute (China), University of Amsterdam (NL), Utrecht University (NL) and the Amsterdam University of Applied Sciences (NL). \r\n\r\nFor a summary <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7w4AwLVKea8\"> check out the video.</a>\r\n\r\nMore at <a href=\"http://www.bestsceneintown.com\"> www.bestsceneintown.com</a>','2011-09-16 09:00:00','2011-09-16 11:00:00','2011-06-30 15:34:25','2011-07-13 13:29:44',1,'2011/07/12/03_18_47_335_Screen_shot_2011_07_12_at_12.17.03_PM.png'),(115,'Vodafone Mobile Clicks Nominees',3,'','2011-09-15 12:30:00','2011-09-15 14:00:00','2011-06-30 15:35:34','2011-07-11 14:48:42',1,NULL),(116,'COMM Lab',6,'','2011-09-16 12:30:00','2011-09-16 14:00:00','2011-06-30 15:35:51','2011-06-30 15:35:51',1,NULL),(117,'Re/designing the Biology of Cities',6,'Cities consume large amounts of resources -- food, fuel, materials -- most of which is transported large distances.  Cities also produce large amounts of waste, most of which is disposed of locally.  How can we spend less money and energy moving resources to cities?  Architects, urban planners, and designers will soon have new tools in hand to address this problem.  This session will present new biological technologies that will enable cities to locally produce food and materials via recycling.  The infrastructure for this new mode of production will look very familiar to residents of Amsterdam; greenhouses and beer brewing.  And just like brewing beer, this production will take place at both the large and the small scale.  This session will have presentations on using microbes to turn cellulose into replacements for petrochemicals (Blue Marble Biomaterials), using algae to recycle sewage into useful biomass (NASA), and growing a city\'s entire food supply in a greenhouse (The Polydome Project); a roundtable discussion with the audience will follow.\r\n\r\nThe 20th century was built on fire and mining.  The 21st will be built using biological systems that are much more efficient.  With a combination of high-tech jobs and distributed production, biological production will move into cities, enabling those cities to make more of the stuff they use.  Locally made materials will supply industry and will allow cities to send less capital overseas to import energy and materials in the form of petroleum. Recycling and production in urban areas will soon look radically different than it does today.\r\n\r\n','2011-09-15 14:45:00','2011-09-15 16:00:00','2011-06-30 15:36:29','2011-07-12 11:26:14',1,NULL),(118,'COMM Lab',6,'','2011-09-16 14:45:00','2011-09-16 16:00:00','2011-06-30 15:36:46','2011-06-30 15:36:46',1,NULL),(119,'tba',8,'','2011-09-15 09:00:00','2011-09-15 11:00:00','2011-06-30 15:37:45','2011-06-30 15:37:45',1,NULL),(120,'ECBN Plenary Session',8,'','2011-09-16 09:00:00','2011-09-16 11:00:00','2011-06-30 15:38:21','2011-06-30 15:38:21',1,NULL),(121,'From Database Cities to Urban Stories',8,'Our cities are increasingly becoming data-rich environments. The ecology of apps, tools, visualizations and other practices that spawn around data cities have the potential to vastly transform the way we understand and inhabit our cities. From crime maps like <a href=\"http://www.everyblock.com/\">EveryBlocks</a> to urban air quality visualizations like <a href=\"http://www.intheair.es/\">In the Air</a>, today issues of urban sustainability and environmental sustainability migrate to these instruments. By employing portable air monitoring devices to measure pollution and fossil fuel in their neighborhoods, \"citizen science\" projects like <a href=\"http://www.pm-air.net/\">AIR</a> enable publics to contest official scientific evidence on issues of environmental sustainability.\r\n\r\nThis session will bring together leading thinkers in academia, industry and government to address some essential questions in the vibrant conversation on the future of cities: What are the promises and perils of the practices and instruments we use today to understand the processes that govern our cities and better manage them? How do we design systems and produce visualizations and lead to active engagement with central issues of our times? What are the successful examples? What role do journalists play in making sense of the data cities? How can citizens in their everyday life gain the ability to affect the urban environment in new ways? \r\n','2011-09-15 12:30:00','2011-09-15 14:00:00','2011-06-30 15:38:49','2011-07-11 15:15:49',1,NULL),(122,'ECBN Pitch session',8,'','2011-09-16 12:30:00','2011-09-16 14:00:00','2011-06-30 15:39:10','2011-06-30 15:39:10',1,NULL),(123,'From Database Cities to Urban Stories',8,'Our cities are increasingly becoming data-rich environments. The ecology of apps, tools, visualizations and other practices that spawn around data cities have the potential to vastly transform the way we understand and inh